<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1924-04-08T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1924-04-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="135" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d135">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">811.348 Z 4/143</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Spain</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Moore</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Madrid</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1924-04-08"><hi rend="italic">April 8,
                                1924</hi></date>.<lb/>[Received April 22.]</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 307</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: With reference to the Department’s
                            instruction No. 73 of March 10th last, I have the honor to report that
                            Major General Julio de Ardanaz has informed this Embassy that there is
                            no objection on the part of the Government to the flight of the airship
                                <hi rend="italic">ZR–3</hi> across Spanish territory on her voyage
                            to the United States. The General has also stated that the Aeronautics
                            Section would take pleasure in aiding the crew of the airship with
                            whatever materials or information may be necessary to make its voyage
                            completely successful.</p>
                        <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Alexander P.
                            Moore</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>